<form class="login-form">
  <div class="bg-img">
    <div class="content">
      <header>Login</header>
      <form action="#">
        <div class="field">
          <span class="user"></span>
          <input
            type="text"
            required
            placeholder="Enter Email"
            id="email-login"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="field space">
          <span class="lock"></span>
          <input
            type="password"
            class="pass-key"
            required
            placeholder="Password"
            id="password-login"
          />
          <span class="show">SHOW</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pass">
          <a href="#">Forgot Password?</a>
        </div>
        <div class="field login-button">
          <input type="submit" value="LOGIN" />
        </div>
      </form>
    </div>
  </div>
</form>

<form class="signup-form">
  <div>
    <label for="username-signup">username:</label>
    <input type="text" id="username-signup" />
  </div>
  <div>
    <label for="email-signup">email:</label>
    <input type="text" id="email-signup" />
  </div>
  <div>
    <label for="password-signup">password:</label>
    <input type="password" id="password-signup" />
  </div>
  <div>
    <label for="password-signup">Github:</label>
    <input type="text" id="github" />
  </div>
  <div>
    <button type="submit">signup</button>
  </div>
</form>

{{! It's important to keep in mind that the front-end JavaScript code 
will not be sent over to the client at the same time as the HTML content. 
The browser will make a new request for the JavaScript 
file after the template has rendered and it sees the linked <script> element. }}
<script src="/javascript/login.js"></script>